TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Impact of Gender Diversity on the Performance of Business Teams: Evidence from a Field Experiment
AU  - Hoogendoorn, Sander
AU  - Oosterbeek, Hessel
AU  - van Praag,  Mirjam
Y1  - 2013/03/04
PY  - 2013
DA  - 2013/07/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.1120.1674
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.1120.1674
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1514
EP  - 1528
VL  - 59
IS  - 7
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper reports on a field experiment conducted to estimate the impact of the share of women in business teams on their performance. Teams consisting of undergraduate students in business studies start up a venture as part of their curriculum. We manipulated the gender composition of teams and assigned students randomly to teams, conditional on their gender. We find that teams with an equal gender mix perform better than male-dominated teams in terms of sales and profits. We explore various mechanisms suggested in the literature to explain this positive effect of gender diversity on performance (including complementarities, learning, monitoring, and conflicts) but find no support for them. This paper was accepted by Jesper S?rensen, organizations.
AB  - This paper reports on a field experiment conducted to estimate the impact of the share of women in business teams on their performance. Teams consisting of undergraduate students in business studies start up a venture as part of their curriculum. We manipulated the gender composition of teams and assigned students randomly to teams, conditional on their gender. We find that teams with an equal gender mix perform better than male-dominated teams in terms of sales and profits. We explore various mechanisms suggested in the literature to explain this positive effect of gender diversity on performance (including complementarities, learning, monitoring, and conflicts) but find no support for them. This paper was accepted by Jesper S?rensen, organizations.
